<DOC><DOCNO> AP880810-0244 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-88 2134EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Seals     08-10 0178</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Britain-Seals,0184</SECOND><HEAD>Seal Scientists Meet in London</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Dead Seals, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Northern European scientists opened a two-daymeeting Wednesday to try to shed light on what is killing seals bythe thousands along their coasts, a sponsor of the gathering said.   The environmental group Greenpeace, which is sponsoring themeeting with the University of London, said the scientists will tryto assess the number of deaths, their cause and remedies.   About 7,000 diseased harbor seals have died since April, abouthalf the population in the North Sea waters of West Germany, theNetherlands, Norway, Denmark and Sweden.   Environmentalists blame the deaths on pollution, but scientistssay they are uncertain about what causes the viral infections thatare killing the animals.   ``While governments argue over who is to blame for the currentcrisis in the North and Baltic seas, the common seal in this areafaces extinction,'' said Greenpeace spokesman Andrew Booth.   The 12 scientists at the meeting come from Britain, Denmark, theNetherlands, West Germany, Norway and Sweden, said Greenpeace pressspokeswomen Sue Adams.</TEXT></DOC>